  "prompt": "What is the difference between wires and cables?",
  "response": "Here are the key differences between wires and cables:\n\nWires:\n1. Single strand of conductive material (usually copper or aluminum)\n2. Typically thin and simple in construction\n3. Used for basic electrical connections\n4. Carry electrical current in a single path\n5. Less complex and less insulated\n6. Can be bare or have minimal insulation\n\nCables:\n1. Multiple wires bundled together\n2. More complex and thicker\n3. Often have multiple insulated conductors\n4. Can carry multiple signals or power simultaneously\n5. More heavily insulated and protected\n6. Used in more complex electrical and communication systems\n7. Can include additional protective layers like sheathing\n8. More durable and suitable for challenging environments\n\nIn summary, a wire is a single conductor, while a cable is a collection of wires grouped together with additional protective features. Cables are more sophisticated and versatile compared to individual wires.",
